We designed the anisotropic nanoribbons based on the relevant length scales of δ18 and λSPhP, as shown in Fig. 1a. The thickness of the ribbons was fixed at 100 nm to suppress the broadband emission. We estimated the volumetric emissivity to be 0.062 for this thickness at room temperature, which is much smaller than the bulk emissivity (~0.9). The design of the width of the ribbon was dependent on λSPhP. It should be noted that the wavelength of SPhPs at the SiO2/vacuum interface is different from that in free space (~10 µm); it is dependent on the geometry of the SiO2 ribbons because the dispersion of SPhPs is now controlled by the coupling between the optical phonon in SiO2 and photons. We determined the dispersion of a thin film using the following analytical formula (see Supplementary Note 8):1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
